main event: The crew of a WV-2 aircraft observed a single object in the sky that was similar in size and brightness to a first-magnitude white star.
interesting points: The object was first observed at an elevation of 45 degrees and an azimuth of 208 degrees, and it remained in sight for approximately 7 minutes before disappearing at an elevation of 38 degrees and an azimuth of 163 degrees.
The object appeared to follow an orbital path and moved at a constant speed.
The object was observed visually without the use of optical aids, and the aircraft was at an altitude of 12,000 feet with a heading of 214 degrees and a true airspeed of 210 knots.
The object was evaluated as a possible satellite.
The report was confirmed on ground radar and tracked for approximately 17 minutes before the object disappeared.
sighted object: a single object similar in size and brightness to a first-magnitude white star
witnesses: the crew of a WV-2 aircraft
